description: The oak tree grove at Newell Park features more than 150 mature, native white (Quercus alba), bur (Quercus macrocarpa), and red oaks in a 10-acre space. Most of the oak trees in this grove were well established when Newell Park was dedicated in 1908. Named after Stanford Newell, a member of the first park board, the oak savannah, or oak openings, exemplifies what most of the city looked like before development. The dense overhead canopy creates plenty of shade for a picnic on a warm summer day. The underground connection of roots and mycorrhizae (a symbiotic association between a fungus and the roots of a vascular plant) ensures the oak grove's survival by sharing water and nutrients.
author: City of Saint Paul

description: Located on Montrose Place next to 2263 Riverwood Place, this butternut has a beautiful wide canopy and multi-stemmed form, which is common characteristic of the species. It is a true specimen due to its large size and good health. Unfortunately, most of the species in the eastern United States has been threatened by a fungal infection known as butternut canker. Due to the isolation from other butternuts, this tree remains unaffected by the butternut canker. Also known as white walnuts, butternuts are in the same family as black walnuts. White walnuts are valued more for their delicious nuts than for their wood. Butternuts are native to the southeastern portion of Minnesota.
author: City of Saint Paul

description: This native specimen tree is located in Mounds Park across from 1027 Thorn Street. Situated atop a small hill, this basswood serves as a landmark in the western area of the park. Each spring the flowers of this basswood tree produce a pleasant fragrance that is enjoyed by not only the park visitors, but the honey bees as well. Their light wood is ideal for making musical instruments as it is easy to work with and has good acoustic properties. The basswood tree is known to have many medicinal qualities used to treat a wide range of ailments such as colds, fevers, infections, and high blood pressure.
author: City of Saint Paul

description: Located in the backyard of 1148 Hawthorne Avenue near Lake Phalen, this apple tree is surely one of the largest in Saint Paul with a trunk diameter of 28 inches and canopy spread of nearly 40 feet. While the exact variety is unknown, the tree produces an abundance of fruit that is reported to make a delicious apple pie. Planted on the southwest corner of the house the large stature of this tree provides shade to the home and deck. This tree can be viewed from the homeowne's driveway on the east side of the property.
author: City of Saint Paul

description: Located below the river bluffs of Crosby Farm Regional Park, this stand of Kentucky coffeetrees is unparalleled in Saint Paul for the number and size of coffeetrees in a single location. While at the northern limit of their growing range, coffeetrees are a valuable landscape tree for boulevards, parks, and residential yards exhibiting an architectural branch structure and interesting seed pods that provide exceptional winter interest. Extensive site enhancement managed by the Saint Paul Environmental Services Unit is reestablishing Crosby Farm's ecologically significant plant communities while allowing greater access to these trees.
author: City of Saint Paul

description: This native tree is located just east of Snelling Avenue at 1490 Eleanor Avenue. The significant size of this tree, with a diameter just 6 inches shy of the current Minnesota state record, and planting location within the homeowner's yard provides beneficial shade reducing summer cooling costs. Hackberry trees are typically found in floodplain forests but are adaptable to a wide range of growing conditions in the urban environment making them ideal shade trees for the boulevard and residential yards.
author: City of Saint Paul

description: Located at the intersection of Holly Avenue and Mackubin Street, this magnificent Bur Oak is a true landmark in the Summit-University neighborhood of Saint Paul. Photographs captured as early as 1890 reveal that this tree was already well established as the surrounding neighborhood grew and developed throughout the 1880's and 1890's. The tree's wide canopy arches over the street enriching the experiential quality of the neighborhood and providing shade to those out on a summer stroll.
author: City of Saint Paul

Breadsmith -- Dumpsters in back inside wooden pen. Contains bread, bagels, cinnamon rolls. Best after 7pm. They throw out their extra bread at the end of the day after closing time. Don't go at 8am, delivery men who will yell at you. Since it shares a dumpster with a paint store, inspect all food well prior to eating. Not the nicest of guys, so don’t let them see you.
Day (tiger) lilies can be found in Lincoln Drive Park (Euclid Ave, off of 10th Ave S going east). Location on map is approximate.

Pine needles are available throughout summer and mid-fall. Most pines seem to grow from Aurora Medical Park on S Washington toward the west (location on map is approximate). Farmers and landscapers use them against wind erosion. Needles aside, you can always eat the pine nuts raw or cooked.

Oak leaves are available throughout summer and mid-fall. Many oaks are toward the river near Lincoln Drive Park and along the Greenway (location on map is approximate). Leaves aside, you can always eat the acorns raw or cooked.

A decent apple tree grows near the Ramada Inn and Visitor’s Bureau off Gateway Dr on N 43rd St (location on map is approximate). The apples are small but flavorful and on public property. Gleaning fallen apples in the afternoon allows bees to eat and calm down, making the harvest safer and easier. Crabapples, though smaller and more tart, can also be found in the area.

Independence Park (a small area off Demers Ave near the Smiley Water Tower)

The city plants flowers and some edible plants with the expectation people can and will take some if they need it. In late summer and mid-fall (Aug-Oct) there are apples and rhubarb every year. Sometimes the strawberry patch produces fruit, but this is hit or miss. The patch has so many runners that a person can take cuttings for a home garden and not spoil the park or the mother plant. Later in the season the city sometimes plants ornamental (but still edible) hot chilies and/or kale.

Note: The rule of the park is to not take everything. Harvest what’s ripe or would otherwise go to waste and clean up what’s no longer good (there’s a compost bin next to the park) to help better the garden for others. If a heavy frost or snow is imminent within the next day, taking more than normal is considered acceptable.

University Park (University Ave & N 23rd St)

Kale and rose hips in fall, day (tiger) lilies and other edible flowers in summer. Mid-September is Potato Bowl and there’s a festival in the park featuring free french fries. You can wait in line for fresh ones, or also a lot get wasted by people who eat a few and discard the rest of the container in the grass.

Note: Go after dusk to avoid harassment from students. Don’t take everything, harvest what’s ripe and tidy up what’s already gone bad.

Urban Development Office (1405 1st Ave N)

Along the sidewalk, you'll find apple trees, huge crab apples, and small, super-sweet plums. If you’re going for a haul larger than what can fit in your hands or pockets, they prefer you come after hours. This is the best time anyway, since bees are most active (and thick here) during the day.

Northern Plains Potato Growers (420 Business Hwy 2)

Depending on the season, more potatoes than the average person sees in a lifetime. Harvest time is mid-fall, so look for the most excess during September and October. Dumpsters are visible from the 5th Ave NE side.

City Dog Park (inside Lincoln Drive Park)

The apple tree is at the end of the City Dog Park (inside Lincoln Drive Park). Doesn’t overlap the fence, so there’s minimal risk of dog waste contamination.
A big patch of sumac at Demers Ave along S Columbia exit ramp. Berries ripe typically in late Aug through mid-Sept.

There's an apple tree behind a white house. The house is owned by Bethany Lutheran College and is currently vacant. They probably won't notice if you go onto the land and grab some apples, especially if they've already fallen.
winnipeg harvest dumpster. potatoes, onions, canned goods, bread, and plenty of nice surprises.
There lots of mulberries on ether side of the fence. Keep an eye on the traffic.
author: Holly Pech

description: Tree outside a community centre that bears a large number of medium-sized, red apples. Apples are very tangy and develop better taste after it gets a bit colder. Fruit off the lower branches can be picked from early September onwards but by October, only the fruit on the upper branches is left. Pretty easy to climb and I easily get 2-5 pounds in a visit.

description:
Dollar Tree 

Often has food with damaged packaging or that is past-date. Canned food, instant foods, sugary foods.

Sometimes cleaning chemicals, soaps, shampoos.

Also has random school supplies, and cheap junk from China.

Check a month or two after major holidays for lots of cards.

Sometimes they lock this dumpster, but generally it is not. It goes in phases.
author: wcbpolish

description:
ALDI Dumpster
Actually 2 dumpsters. The "organic waste" one is great for finding fresh produce, the other is a source of damaged/post date canned, box, packaged foods.
Currently (summer 2015) throw trash out at between noon and 3pm, so this is the best time to get it- before it spoils.
There have been signs posted asking people to stop "stealing" trash, with comments about calling the the cops.
Many locals check these dumpsters regularly.
Somewhat "dirty" trash (wear gloves, don't dig too deep for food items)

description:
BOOKS!
This is where donated books that are not good enough for the library are thrown out! Lots of good reads! Generally no "trash" in with the books.
I prefer this to visiting the library. After reading the books, I put them in the neighborhood mini-libraries for others to enjoy.
Common book types: Cheesy romance paperbacks, old hardcovers, old textbooks, juvenile fiction, LOTS of theology/religion. Mostly still in reasonable condition to read - some in great condition!
